He added: 'This is a lawsuit brought by rich people who live in silk and comfort, who only inhale perfume and who want to stop this lady from living.'

When the matter went to court in 2012, Ms Maertens said: 'I'm angry and I feel persecuted. For rich people, it's certain that a chip stall in front of them is going to be annoying but us, we have to work for a living.

'They complain about the noise and the smell of chips, but if you want peace and quiet, you don't buy an apartment at the foot of the slopes.'

When Sir Lindsay took over L'Oreal's in the mid-1980s, annual sales were 3.7 billion dollars, and when he stood down they were 14.5 billion dollars.

Much of the success was based on brilliant marketing, including slogans like 'Because You're Worth it'.

As well as skiing, Sir Lindsay, who is now 68, is passionate about numerous sports including motor racing and sailing. He was knighted in 2005.

 

